data.content:
Yes — MSTest 3.4+ supports generic `DynamicData<T1, T2, ...>` which gives you compile-time type safety:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData<string, bool>(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string, bool)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Key differences:**
- `DynamicData<string, bool>` — generic type params enforce that data matches the test method signature at compile time
- Data source returns `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` (tuples) instead of `object[]` — no boxing, no casting, and mismatched types are caught by the compiler

Requires `MSTest.TestFramework` ≥ 3.4 (via `MSTest` meta-package or directly).
